    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Educational Deep Dive: The History and Science of QR Codes</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Ever wondered where these squares came from? The Quick Response (QR) code was actually invented in 1994 by <strong>Denso Wave</strong>, a Japanese automotive company. Originally, they weren't used for websites—they were used to track car parts in high-speed manufacturing lines!
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        So, how do they work? Unlike a traditional barcode which only stores data in one dimension (left to right), a QR code is <strong>two-dimensional</strong>. It stores data both horizontally and vertically. The three big squares in the corners (finding patterns) help your phone camera figure out which way is "up," allowing the code to be read from any angle instantly.
    </p>

